12.7 Tables: gt for polished static tables
The gt package (“grammar of tables,” deliberately named to echo ggplot2’s philosophy) turns a summarized data frame into a publication-quality formatted table:

library(gt)

static_file |&gt;
  group_by(SchoolName) |&gt;
  summarize(n_students = n(), avg_scale_score = mean(ScaleScore, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  arrange(desc(avg_scale_score)) |&gt;
  head(10) |&gt;
  gt() |&gt;
  tab_header(title = "Top 10 Schools by Average Scale Score") |&gt;
  fmt_number(columns = avg_scale_score, decimals = 1)

This is the kind of table you’d put directly into a report someone is reading top to bottom — formatted, titled, and ready to present, rather than a raw printed data frame.

13.3 Step 2: Clean and combine

tidy_data &lt;- raw_list |&gt;
  clean_names() |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(scale_score))   # drop non-assessed records for this particular analysis

14.6 Explore the Data

static_file |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(Performance)) |&gt;
  select(SchoolName, DistrictName, Subject, Performance, ScaleScore) |&gt;
  datatable(filter = "top", options = list(pageLength = 8))

This single chunk hands your audience a live, searchable, filterable version of the underlying data, directly inside the presentation — rather than a static screenshot of a table they can’t interact with.
